Tokens

This module provides the tokens used during lexing, parsing and interpreting a Words program.

class words.token_types.lexer_token.DelimLexerToken(word: Word)

A delimiter token is used to start and end a series of values.

class Types(value)

An enumeration.

parse(tokens: Iterator[LexerToken]) → None

Delimiter lexer tokens cannot be parsed by themselves. They are parsed by the preceding function token.

Parameters

tokens – The list of lexer tokens, which might be used during parsing of this token depending on it’s type.

Returns

None

class words.token_types.lexer_token.KeywordLexerToken(word: Word)

A keyword token holds builtin words that mean something in the language. These keywords cannot be used as variable names.

class words.token_types.lexer_token.OpLexerToken(word: Word)

An operator token holds a Keyword that is used as an operator on literals or identifiers

class Types(value)

An enumeration.

parse(tokens: Iterator[LexerToken]) → Union[ArithmeticOperatorParserToken, BooleanOperatorParserToken, DictionaryOperatorParserToken]

Parse the lexer token into a parser token. :param tokens: The list of lexer tokens, which might be used during parsing of this token depending on it’s type. :return: One of the three operator parser token types: ArithmeticOperatorParserToken, BooleanOperatorParserToken or DictionaryOperatorParserToken, based on the type of lexer token.

class words.token_types.parser_token.ArithmeticOperatorParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, value: str)

An arithmetic operator parser token represents an arithmetic operation. For example the addition operation. It holds both the type of operation, as well as the values it will operate on.

execute(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Execute the arithmetic operation.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack to use for executing the token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

Raises

  • StackSizeException – An arithmetic operator always needs two values to run.

  • NotImplementedError – If an undefined operator is specified it cannot run.

class words.token_types.parser_token.BooleanOperatorParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, value: str)

An boolean operator parser token represents a boolean operation. For example the equality operation. It holds both the type of operation, as well as the values it will operate on.

execute(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Execute the boolean operation.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack to use for executing the token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

Raises

  • StackSizeException – A boolean operation always needs two values to run.

  • NotImplementedError – If an undefined operator is specified it cannot run.

class words.token_types.parser_token.CopyParserToken(debug_data: DebugData)

A Copy Parser Token represents a COPY keyword. The COPY keyword duplicates the topmost value on the stack.

class words.token_types.parser_token.DictionaryOperatorParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, value: str, variable_name: str)

A dictionary operator parser token represents a dictionary operation. Dictionary operators are used for interacting with the dictionary. For example the assign operator assigns the top value from the stack to the provided identifier in the dictionary.

execute(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Execute the dictionary operation.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack to use for executing the token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

Raises

NotImplementedError – If an undefined operator is specified it cannot run.

class words.token_types.parser_token.DictionaryToken

A visitable token that is stored in the dictionary.

class RemovedDictionaryToken

Placeholder for tokens that are removed from the dictionary.

abstract visit(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

The visit method is used for tokens that might have some other use after the initial execute. For example the function parser token is placed in the dictionary during execution, and run during visiting.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack used for visiting this token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary used for visiting this token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after this token has been visited..

class words.token_types.parser_token.FunctionParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, name: str, parameters: List[ParserToken], body: List[ParserToken])
A function parser token represents a function. It can be executed to place it in the dictionary and visited to run

the statements in the body of the function.

A debug string is used for providing better error messages during both parsing and at runtime.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

class words.token_types.parser_token.IfParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, if_body: List[ParserToken], else_body: Optional[List[ParserToken]] = None)

The if token represents an if statement, with an optional else statement.

debug_str() → str

A debug string is used for providing better error messages during both parsing and at runtime.

execute(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Either run the if or else body, based on the predicate.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack to use for executing the token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

Raises

InvalidPredicateException – If the predicate does not return a boolean value the if statement cannot know if it should run.

class words.token_types.parser_token.VariableParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, value: str)

The variable token represents a variable. The variable token gets placed in the dictionary.

debug_str() → str

A debug string is used for providing better error messages during both parsing and at runtime.

execute(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Execute the variable to place it in the dictionary, with Unassigned as its value.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack to use for executing the token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

Raises

IdentifierPreviouslyDefinedException – Since shadowing is not allowed, a variable cannot be defined twice.

visit(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Visiting a variable retrieves its assigned value and places it on the stack. :param stack: :param dictionary: :return:

class words.token_types.parser_token.WhileParserToken(debug_data: DebugData, predicate: List[ParserToken], statements: List[ParserToken])
The while token represents a while loop. It holds a predicate that is checked every loop and the statements that

should be executed as long as the predicate holds true.

debug_str() → str

A debug string is used for providing better error messages during both parsing and at runtime.

execute(stack: list, dictionary: dict) → Tuple[list, dict]

Run the while loop as long as the predicate holds true.

Parameters

  • stack – The stack to use for executing the token.

  • dictionary – The dictionary to use for executing the token.

Returns

The stack and dictionary after executing the token.

Raises

InvalidPredicateException – If the predicate does not return a boolean value the while loop cannot know if it should run.
